1
00:00:07,215 --> 00:00:11,181
[SPEAKER_04]: And now to our second candidate, Maria Fernanda Espinosa.

2
00:00:11,301 --> 00:00:12,783
[SPEAKER_04]: She has served twice.

3
00:00:13,364 --> 00:00:14,766
[SPEAKER_04]: Women always want to do it twice.

4
00:00:14,786 --> 00:00:16,949
[SPEAKER_04]: They do it so well that people ask them to do it again.

5
00:00:17,450 --> 00:00:21,496
[SPEAKER_04]: Twice as Ecuador's foreign minister, she was the Minister of Defence as well.

6
00:00:22,297 --> 00:00:28,882
[SPEAKER_04]: In 2018, she was elected president of the 73rd session of the UN General Assembly.

7
00:00:28,922 --> 00:00:38,050
[SPEAKER_04]: She's the first woman from Latin America to have that job, and only the fourth woman in the history of the entire assembly.

8
00:00:38,990 --> 00:00:43,954
[SPEAKER_04]: Maria Fernanda Espinosa is nominated by Antigua and Barbados.

9
00:00:44,054 --> 00:00:47,257
[SPEAKER_04]: Please join me in welcoming Maria Fernanda Espinosa.

10
00:00:57,475 --> 00:00:58,896
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you very much.

11
00:00:59,076 --> 00:01:03,259
[SPEAKER_04]: I love she's got good fashion sense.

12
00:01:07,482 --> 00:01:12,665
[SPEAKER_04]: Maria Fernanda Espinosa, you have five minutes to settle your vision.

13
00:01:12,905 --> 00:01:17,048
[SPEAKER_04]: Why do you want this toughest of jobs and what are you going to do with it?

14
00:01:17,408 --> 00:01:21,511
[SPEAKER_04]: And I will give you a warning at four minutes.

15
00:01:24,112 --> 00:01:24,833
[ESPINOSA]: Thank you, Lise.

16
00:01:26,217 --> 00:01:31,780
[ESPINOSA]: Excellencies and friends, it is a true pleasure to be back in London.

17
00:01:32,581 --> 00:01:43,127
[ESPINOSA]: I was here already in January at the invitation of UN and UK and what I did is I spoke about a world in crisis.

18
00:01:44,508 --> 00:01:53,814
[ESPINOSA]: Conflicts, famine, climate shocks, whining of global cooperation, the UN under strain.

19
00:01:55,596 --> 00:01:58,819
[ESPINOSA]: And I wish I could say things have improved.

20
00:01:59,860 --> 00:02:02,062
[ESPINOSA]: And we know they haven't.

21
00:02:03,643 --> 00:02:07,306
[ESPINOSA]: That is why I want to speak plainly this evening.

22
00:02:08,867 --> 00:02:11,209
[ESPINOSA]: Nobody wants another careful speech.

23
00:02:12,310 --> 00:02:14,472
[ESPINOSA]: What we need is we need action.

24
00:02:15,994 --> 00:02:18,616
[ESPINOSA]: And I want to focus on four things this evening.

25
00:02:19,517 --> 00:02:23,200
[ESPINOSA]: First, I want to talk about prevention.

26
00:02:24,619 --> 00:02:34,564
[ESPINOSA]: The UN was created to prevent war, a solemn promise made when bombs were still raining down in this city.

27
00:02:35,544 --> 00:02:40,307
[ESPINOSA]: But too often, the UN arrives after the worst has happened.

28
00:02:41,307 --> 00:02:43,508
[ESPINOSA]: What we need is bold ideas.

29
00:02:44,669 --> 00:02:49,191
[ESPINOSA]: As Secretary General, I will establish a prevention and early action hub.

30
00:02:50,191 --> 00:02:52,274
[ESPINOSA]: And its purpose is very simple.

31
00:02:53,054 --> 00:03:02,306
[ESPINOSA]: To ensure that warnings reach decision makers early and that action can be taken before the situation gets worse.

32
00:03:03,789 --> 00:03:10,474
[ESPINOSA]: The Secretary-General must always be ready to lead these efforts.

33
00:03:11,235 --> 00:03:24,185
[ESPINOSA]: She must focus on addressing the consequences of a crisis, whether that's diplomacy to secure life-saving support or working together to manage energy shocks or food shortages.

34
00:03:25,193 --> 00:03:36,639
[ESPINOSA]: And the Secretary-General must recognise when the UN needs to be centre stage, but also when it's a better place to play a supporting role.

35
00:03:38,059 --> 00:03:44,783
[ESPINOSA]: Second, we must put people at the heart of development, not the UN.

36
00:03:45,993 --> 00:03:53,338
[ESPINOSA]: With support from countries like the UK, the UN has saved and transformed millions of lives.

37
00:03:54,078 --> 00:03:56,179
[ESPINOSA]: We must not forget that.

38
00:03:57,560 --> 00:04:01,983
[ESPINOSA]: The Sustainable Development Goals remain the right ambition.

39
00:04:02,923 --> 00:04:05,325
[ESPINOSA]: But ambition is not action.

40
00:04:06,165 --> 00:04:10,368
[ESPINOSA]: Countries do not need another summit or another slogan.

41
00:04:11,289 --> 00:04:12,810
[ESPINOSA]: They need the money.

42
00:04:13,736 --> 00:04:17,680
[ESPINOSA]: the technology and the institutions to deliver for their people.

43
00:04:20,302 --> 00:04:24,165
[ESPINOSA]: Developments cannot be delivered from New York.

44
00:04:25,106 --> 00:04:26,367
[ESPINOSA]: I strongly believe that.

45
00:04:27,488 --> 00:04:37,938
[ESPINOSA]: We need a leaner UN that can focus on where it adds most value, a local first approach that empowers people and governments.

46
00:04:38,941 --> 00:04:45,403
[ESPINOSA]: Third, we need to work together to harness and manage the power of AI.

47
00:04:46,303 --> 00:04:47,663
[ESPINOSA]: This is not a tech issue.

48
00:04:48,504 --> 00:04:50,164
[ESPINOSA]: It is a security issue.

49
00:04:50,904 --> 00:04:52,465
[ESPINOSA]: It is a jobs issue.

50
00:04:53,425 --> 00:04:55,606
[ESPINOSA]: It is a rights issue.

51
00:04:56,706 --> 00:05:00,527
[ESPINOSA]: No single state or company should call the shots.

52
00:05:01,509 --> 00:05:17,133
[ESPINOSA]: The UN cannot and should not regulate everything, but it must bring people together, including civil society and young people, those that are normally shut out of these conversations.

53
00:05:17,753 --> 00:05:22,455
[ESPINOSA]: And finally, we have to change the UN for the better, not the cheaper.

54
00:05:23,455 --> 00:05:25,037
[ESPINOSA]: Yes, we have to cut costs.

55
00:05:25,457 --> 00:05:26,378
[ESPINOSA]: That is essential.

56
00:05:26,659 --> 00:05:28,601
[ESPINOSA]: But that cannot be our only goal.

57
00:05:28,741 --> 00:05:30,983
[ESPINOSA]: Reform must mean doing better.

58
00:05:31,664 --> 00:05:35,308
[ESPINOSA]: That means focusing on demand, not supply.

59
00:05:35,829 --> 00:05:42,796
[ESPINOSA]: That means being prepared to let go of some functions entirely and focus on the organization's greatest strengths.

60
00:05:43,637 --> 00:05:55,844
[ESPINOSA]: Ultimately, you, in this room and outside, will not judge the UN by the number of reform initiatives, nor by whether it has improved your lives and your future.

61
00:05:56,705 --> 00:05:59,586
[ESPINOSA]: That is the UN I want to build.

62
00:06:00,387 --> 00:06:03,929
[ESPINOSA]: With governments, with a strong leadership team, and with you, of course.

63
00:06:04,509 --> 00:06:09,032
[ESPINOSA]: I do not pretend to have all the answers, but this is not a task for one individual.

64
00:06:09,372 --> 00:06:12,574
[ESPINOSA]: The United Nations is a promise we must all keep.

65
00:06:13,814 --> 00:06:15,695
[ESPINOSA]: So here's what I offer.

66
00:06:16,836 --> 00:06:20,459
[ESPINOSA]: A life devoted to serving my country and the international community.

67
00:06:21,079 --> 00:06:27,344
[ESPINOSA]: An insider-outsider perspective as someone who understands the system but is not captured by it.

68
00:06:28,164 --> 00:06:34,349
[ESPINOSA]: A track record of working across all the pillars of the UN and with people from all walks of life.

69
00:06:35,411 --> 00:06:45,698
[ESPINOSA]: a firm commitment without fear or favor to the values of the Charter, to international law, and to serving all Member States and the world 8 billion people.

70
00:06:46,518 --> 00:06:56,965
[ESPINOSA]: This summer, I suspect many of you will be hoping that England's men's team will lift the World Cup after 60 long years of waiting.

71
00:06:58,385 --> 00:07:03,749
[ESPINOSA]: Well, it has been 80 years of waiting for a woman to lead the UN.

72
00:07:05,317 --> 00:07:14,222
[ESPINOSA]: So this is our opportunity to show the UN can walk the talk on equality and results.

73
00:07:14,522 --> 00:07:17,063
[ESPINOSA]: This is the United Nations I'm prepared to build.

74
00:07:17,464 --> 00:07:20,785
[ESPINOSA]: Not a perfect institution, but a serious, compassionate one.

75
00:07:21,346 --> 00:07:26,528
[ESPINOSA]: Not a louder UN, but a more relevant one that delivers where it matters most.

76
00:07:26,909 --> 00:07:27,409
[ESPINOSA]: I thank you.

77
00:07:36,692 --> 00:07:45,750
[SPEAKER_04]: So you've talked about the wars, you've talked about the moments where the UN has to be centre stage, you've mentioned that no one power should call the shots.

78
00:07:45,851 --> 00:07:46,171
[SPEAKER_04]: Why?

79
00:07:48,707 --> 00:07:55,132
[SPEAKER_04]: talents, skills, experience do you have that make you the person to accomplish that?

80
00:07:55,193 --> 00:08:05,101
[SPEAKER_04]: You were, after all, the president of the General Assembly during President Trump's first term, where the issues of resources and relevance were really accentuated.

81
00:08:05,401 --> 00:08:06,222
[SPEAKER_04]: What did you learn then?

82
00:08:06,242 --> 00:08:12,888
[ESPINOSA]: Well, I think I have the experience to navigate in turbulent waters.

83
00:08:13,614 --> 00:08:16,715
[ESPINOSA]: I think the UN has never been Disneyland.

84
00:08:17,036 --> 00:08:31,002
[ESPINOSA]: I think that what is important is to see a secretary general that is impartial, that is able to build bridges, to work with everybody.

85
00:08:31,502 --> 00:08:34,503
[ESPINOSA]: I have shown that when I was president of the General Assembly.

86
00:08:35,024 --> 00:08:37,425
[ESPINOSA]: I think we need a secretary general that is

87
00:08:39,214 --> 00:08:51,700
[ESPINOSA]: 360 secretary-general that knows every pillar of the UN, that is not a person that is not a single-issue person, but more like a Renaissance leader.

88
00:08:53,746 --> 00:09:10,637
[ESPINOSA]: You also need, what I just said, Liz, you need an insider-outsider, knowing how the UN works, its potential, its challenges, but have, you know, been able to not be captured by the UN.

89
00:09:10,677 --> 00:09:18,102
[ESPINOSA]: I have never worked for the UN, but served the UN in many ways through the UN for about 25 years.

90
00:09:21,104 --> 00:09:25,267
[SPEAKER_04]: I think António Guterres would have also called himself an insider-outsider, and yet here it is.

91
00:09:25,767 --> 00:09:27,248
[SPEAKER_04]: He's not at the center.

92
00:09:27,268 --> 00:09:29,410
[SPEAKER_04]: He's not with the UN at the center stage.

93
00:09:30,150 --> 00:09:32,672
[SPEAKER_04]: In one word, what quality do you have that can make a difference?

94
00:09:33,872 --> 00:09:34,253
[SPEAKER_04]: Poet.

95
00:09:35,473 --> 00:09:35,834
[SPEAKER_04]: Poet?

96
00:09:36,434 --> 00:09:36,674
[ESPINOSA]: Yes.

97
00:09:37,875 --> 00:09:38,936
[ESPINOSA]: I'm a poet.

98
00:09:39,076 --> 00:09:41,657
[ESPINOSA]: I strongly believe in the power of words.

99
00:09:42,358 --> 00:09:45,040
[ESPINOSA]: I strongly believe in the power of narratives.

100
00:09:45,200 --> 00:09:46,360
[SPEAKER_04]: So communication skills.

101
00:09:46,681 --> 00:09:50,163
[ESPINOSA]: Communication, but also being faithful to what you say.

102
00:09:50,868 --> 00:09:51,568
[ESPINOSA]: Okay.

103
00:09:51,688 --> 00:09:53,549
[ESPINOSA]: And I think it's absolutely important.

104
00:09:53,709 --> 00:10:00,572
[ESPINOSA]: As a poet, I learn, first of all, to observe, to deep listen, and to act, and act firmly.

105
00:10:01,152 --> 00:10:01,412
[ESPINOSA]: Okay.

106
00:10:01,432 --> 00:10:05,734
[ESPINOSA]: And I also, of course, learn about beauty and about creativity and innovation.

107
00:10:07,227 --> 00:10:11,448
[SPEAKER_04]: We're going to give you some questions from the audience, but first we need to hear some commitments from you.

108
00:10:11,468 --> 00:10:24,551
[SPEAKER_04]: The 148 billion campaign of which the UK Association of the UN is a member has called on all candidates to commit publicly during this campaign to five principles.

109
00:10:24,771 --> 00:10:27,151
[SPEAKER_04]: And everyone here will remember what you said.

110
00:10:27,311 --> 00:10:28,851
[SPEAKER_04]: So please think carefully.

111
00:10:29,732 --> 00:10:36,173
[SPEAKER_04]: Publishing financial disclosures, engaging with civil society, participating in

112
00:10:37,139 --> 00:10:52,308
[SPEAKER_04]: transparent General Assembly and Security Council processes, respecting Article 100 of the UN Charter, as you know, that means independence from member states, and avoiding conflicts of interest with any current UN role.

113
00:10:53,549 --> 00:10:55,690
[SPEAKER_04]: Are these principles important, and if so, why?

114
00:10:56,611 --> 00:10:57,992
[ESPINOSA]: I think that they're vital.

115
00:10:58,592 --> 00:11:04,676
[ESPINOSA]: When I think about integrity, I don't think that integrity should be proclaimed.

116
00:11:05,476 --> 00:11:06,417
[ESPINOSA]: It should be earned.

117
00:11:07,423 --> 00:11:13,329
[ESPINOSA]: through consistent behavior, and I can show that throughout my 25 years of career and public life.

118
00:11:14,109 --> 00:11:22,578
[ESPINOSA]: The second very important issue is I would sign the five principles that I read carefully right away, just now.

119
00:11:22,598 --> 00:11:26,261
[ESPINOSA]: We'll get that from you.

120
00:11:26,321 --> 00:11:32,047
[ESPINOSA]: When I was exploring the possibility of putting my name forward as Secretary General,

121
00:11:32,978 --> 00:11:38,520
[ESPINOSA]: I was the executive director of a very small NGO, not a UN agency.

122
00:11:40,321 --> 00:11:50,524
[ESPINOSA]: Before I started the consultations, I stepped down from my job just in case there was perception of conflict of interest.

123
00:11:50,624 --> 00:11:52,385
[ESPINOSA]: The issue of civil society,

124
00:11:54,388 --> 00:11:56,709
[ESPINOSA]: It's a little bit of who I am.

125
00:11:57,430 --> 00:12:03,174
[ESPINOSA]: In civil societies, participation and engagement is not only about ticking the box.

126
00:12:04,035 --> 00:12:10,080
[ESPINOSA]: It is about understanding that the huge implementation gap of the United Nations

127
00:12:10,946 --> 00:12:27,595
[ESPINOSA]: is due to the lack of ownership, the lack of co-responsibility and lack of space of civil society to do the advice, the advocacy, the translation of UN decision-making into the daily life of people.

128
00:12:27,955 --> 00:12:31,016
[ESPINOSA]: So the role of civil society is absolutely vital.

129
00:12:31,336 --> 00:12:41,358
[ESPINOSA]: Disclosing the financial, of course, not at the beginning and at the end, but during the process as well, ready to do that, very happy to do that, of course.

130
00:12:41,678 --> 00:12:42,078
[SPEAKER_04]: Okay.

131
00:12:42,238 --> 00:12:43,958
[SPEAKER_04]: That will make many people here very happy.

132
00:12:44,398 --> 00:12:54,440
[SPEAKER_04]: Your first question from the audience, David Cheeseman, who's from the UNA UK, he's a member, convenes a working group on accountability and the UN Security Council.

133
00:12:55,080 --> 00:12:55,620
[SPEAKER_04]: Veto.

134
00:12:56,281 --> 00:13:10,808
[SPEAKER_04]: His question, as Secretary General, what would you do to stop vetoes in the Security Council blocking credible action, especially when it comes to addressing, I'd like to add the word preventing, mass atrocities?

135
00:13:12,329 --> 00:13:12,789
[SPEAKER_04]: The veto.

136
00:13:13,889 --> 00:13:14,970
[SPEAKER_04]: What would you do to stop them?

137
00:13:16,011 --> 00:13:17,171
[ESPINOSA]: The veto power.

138
00:13:17,491 --> 00:13:18,852
[ESPINOSA]: I'm assuming you would want to stop them.

139
00:13:19,696 --> 00:13:23,061
[ESPINOSA]: What I'm saying is that the veto power is written in the Charter.

140
00:13:23,381 --> 00:13:25,464
[ESPINOSA]: It's a principle that is in the Charter.

141
00:13:26,045 --> 00:13:28,368
[ESPINOSA]: And I think we have to be very frank and honest.

142
00:13:28,809 --> 00:13:32,073
[ESPINOSA]: What is the space of movement of the Secretary General?

143
00:13:32,481 --> 00:13:45,393
[ESPINOSA]: The Secretary General should provide good offices, create the platforms for member states, especially the P5 and the members of the Security Council, to come together to discuss issues, to respond quickly.

144
00:13:45,893 --> 00:13:54,381
[ESPINOSA]: That's where my early action hub makes sense, because the role of the UN is to prevent wars and protect people.

145
00:13:54,661 --> 00:14:00,285
[ESPINOSA]: You don't think there should be a veto when it comes to the worst abuses, the worst violations?

146
00:14:00,345 --> 00:14:07,990
[ESPINOSA]: I can have my personal views on this, but I think what we're talking here is what is the role of the Secretary General.

147
00:14:08,310 --> 00:14:21,600
[ESPINOSA]: And the role of the Secretary General is a quiet diplomacy, back channels, to have a permanent and constant interaction and communication with the members of the Security Council, including the P5.

148
00:14:22,120 --> 00:14:24,202
[ESPINOSA]: Here, my personal opinion doesn't count.

149
00:14:24,542 --> 00:14:34,733
[ESPINOSA]: I will be the chief administrative officer of the UN, the lead diplomat, the lead advocate, but I cannot reinterpret the Charter, unfortunately.

150
00:14:34,753 --> 00:14:40,578
[SPEAKER_04]: So, just to be absolutely clear, just a very short answer, you would do nothing to stop vetoes from being used?

151
00:14:41,299 --> 00:14:49,606
[ESPINOSA]: I can use my good offices in talking to the members of the Security Council, especially to the permanent five, of course.

152
00:14:49,886 --> 00:14:51,148
[ESPINOSA]: It doesn't need to be public.

153
00:14:51,288 --> 00:14:53,209
[ESPINOSA]: It doesn't need to make headlines.

154
00:14:53,469 --> 00:14:56,092
[ESPINOSA]: That's part of the job of the Secretary General.

155
00:14:56,612 --> 00:14:58,374
[SPEAKER_04]: We have a question from the audience.

156
00:14:58,894 --> 00:15:01,656
[SPEAKER_04]: Kimber and Ryan from the Advocacy Academy.

157
00:15:05,280 --> 00:15:05,440
[ESPINOSA]: No?

158
00:15:06,120 --> 00:15:06,861
[ESPINOSA]: Yes, all good.

159
00:15:09,787 --> 00:15:10,988
[ESPINOSA]: Go ahead.

160
00:15:12,789 --> 00:15:23,375
[SPEAKER_00]: So young people from our movement have reported feeling hopelessness around the future they are inheriting, facing an economic system and state institutions that do not value them.

161
00:15:23,996 --> 00:15:28,098
[SPEAKER_00]: How would the United Nations create a more hopeful future for young people?

162
00:15:28,598 --> 00:15:33,401
[SPEAKER_00]: What would a youth-centered economic system look like, and why is it not being delivered?

163
00:15:33,421 --> 00:15:38,084
[SPEAKER_04]: A more hopeful future for young people, give them a role in decision-making.

164
00:15:39,817 --> 00:15:46,959
[ESPINOSA]: Well, now it's in fashion to say, you know, young people are important, youth are important.

165
00:15:48,019 --> 00:15:55,141
[ESPINOSA]: In the process of negotiating the pact of the future, we came out with a declaration for future generations.

166
00:15:55,941 --> 00:16:01,083
[ESPINOSA]: And the truth is that young people are not the future, they are the present.

167
00:16:01,710 --> 00:16:05,955
[ESPINOSA]: They have to be part of the conversation, part of the decision making.

168
00:16:06,516 --> 00:16:11,942
[ESPINOSA]: If you look at the team that is working with me right now, most of them are under 30.

169
00:16:12,443 --> 00:16:15,967
[ESPINOSA]: And I listen to them because they are the most creative.

170
00:16:16,067 --> 00:16:18,751
[ESPINOSA]: They are the smartest, the well-informed.

171
00:16:19,251 --> 00:16:20,672
[ESPINOSA]: And what would you do to include them?

172
00:16:21,052 --> 00:16:28,314
[ESPINOSA]: Well, first of all, we have the Declaration on Future Generations, a new and I applaud that a new office for young people.

173
00:16:28,674 --> 00:16:36,397
[ESPINOSA]: But basically, I would recruit as part of my senior team, young people, I'm working with them right now, and I will ensure

174
00:16:36,777 --> 00:16:49,408
[ESPINOSA]: that decision-making in the House brings in the advice, the voice and the space for young people to be part of a new multilateralism of the 21st century.

175
00:16:49,729 --> 00:16:58,236
[ESPINOSA]: Not to tick the box, but to make them part of the decision-making in the House, respecting, of course, the intergovernmental nature of the United Nations.

176
00:16:58,476 --> 00:17:00,698
[ESPINOSA]: But they are the agents of today, not of tomorrow.

177
00:17:01,359 --> 00:17:03,401
[SPEAKER_04]: Kim Run, apply for the job if she gets the job.

178
00:17:04,677 --> 00:17:14,803
[SPEAKER_04]: Okay, another question from the floor, Andrew Gilmore, who's a trustee of the United Nations Association of the United Kingdom, and he's a former Assistant Secretary General for Human Rights.

179
00:17:15,163 --> 00:17:16,404
[SPEAKER_04]: Andrew, the floor is yours.

180
00:17:17,779 --> 00:17:19,519
[SPEAKER_04]: 10,000 steps for you tonight, sir.

181
00:17:19,719 --> 00:17:20,380
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you so much.

182
00:17:20,880 --> 00:17:21,300
[SPEAKER_01]: Good evening.

183
00:17:21,860 --> 00:17:34,462
[SPEAKER_01]: As part of the warm-up this evening before you came on, we were shown an opinion poll that reflected that of all the many areas of activity of the UN, it's the UN's performance in human rights is the lowest.

184
00:17:35,662 --> 00:17:43,664
[SPEAKER_01]: The last Secretary General, Ban Ki-moon, about 12 years ago, launched a major initiative called the Human Rights Upfront Initiative.

185
00:17:43,704 --> 00:17:44,464
[SPEAKER_01]: Many consider it

186
00:17:45,241 --> 00:17:48,686
[SPEAKER_01]: the most important initiative ever in the history of the UN in human rights.

187
00:17:49,488 --> 00:17:57,961
[SPEAKER_01]: Rather sadly, it's been allowed to expire slowly, and I was wondering if you would consider re-initiating it.

188
00:17:59,345 --> 00:17:59,965
[ESPINOSA]: This was in 2013.

189
00:18:00,005 --> 00:18:01,385
[ESPINOSA]: Thank you, Moon.

190
00:18:01,806 --> 00:18:10,528
[ESPINOSA]: First of all, I think all good initiatives from the past and the current administration are not a leader of slash and burn.

191
00:18:11,048 --> 00:18:16,969
[ESPINOSA]: All the good examples, all the good initiatives in the three pillars of the UN, of course, I will embrace them.

192
00:18:17,489 --> 00:18:22,250
[ESPINOSA]: If they became out of date, I will look at that, of course.

193
00:18:22,610 --> 00:18:29,192
[ESPINOSA]: But coming back to the human rights issue, this is part of the three pillars of the UN.

194
00:18:29,652 --> 00:18:33,717
[ESPINOSA]: Human rights is part of the job description of the UN.

195
00:18:34,177 --> 00:18:41,905
[ESPINOSA]: Everything we do, everything the organisation does, has to really look at human dignity.

196
00:18:42,806 --> 00:18:49,893
[ESPINOSA]: Human dignity has to be at the centre of everything we do in development, everything we do in peace and security.

197
00:18:50,573 --> 00:18:51,533
[ESPINOSA]: and believe me.

198
00:18:51,953 --> 00:19:00,255
[SPEAKER_04]: Would you do like Ban Ki-moon and do this a very specific process of reform to put human rights at the center of everything the UN does?

199
00:19:00,335 --> 00:19:02,396
[SPEAKER_04]: He launched a specific initiative.

200
00:19:02,976 --> 00:19:12,778
[ESPINOSA]: Well, right now I would say every action that the UN does has to embed human dignity and human rights.

201
00:19:13,348 --> 00:19:20,013
[ESPINOSA]: I don't know if there is, you know, the right environment to have a dedicated initiative.

202
00:19:20,313 --> 00:19:32,342
[ESPINOSA]: What I can say, however, is the overall budget of the UN depends on how you come from one to three percent of the entire budget of the UN is dedicated to human rights.

203
00:19:32,783 --> 00:19:34,204
[ESPINOSA]: And this tells you something.

204
00:19:34,484 --> 00:19:36,245
[ESPINOSA]: We need to do more and better.

205
00:19:37,666 --> 00:19:40,610
[ESPINOSA]: in a context of austerity that we're living today.

206
00:19:41,331 --> 00:19:50,442
[ESPINOSA]: Every good idea, every good idea is of course of you, especially if it has to do with strengthening the human rights pillar of the organization.

207
00:19:51,598 --> 00:19:58,463
[SPEAKER_04]: A question now from the London clean energy round table.

208
00:19:58,623 --> 00:20:02,105
[SPEAKER_04]: It's an emerging technology and innovation platform.

209
00:20:02,766 --> 00:20:19,558
[SPEAKER_04]: In a world facing escalating climate energy and geopolitical crisis, how would you strengthen collaboration between governments, industry, youth, civil society to accelerate implementation rather than only negotiations and commitments?

210
00:20:19,598 --> 00:20:21,179
[SPEAKER_04]: In other words, just talking shops.

211
00:20:23,232 --> 00:20:29,456
[ESPINOSA]: The issue of building networks and partnerships is absolutely vital in the world of today.

212
00:20:30,016 --> 00:20:39,222
[ESPINOSA]: When we speak about climate change, we understood a long time ago that climate change is not anymore an environmental issue.

213
00:20:40,123 --> 00:20:49,129
[ESPINOSA]: We understood that climate shocks can trigger conflict, can alter entire macroeconomics of a country.

214
00:20:50,035 --> 00:20:54,136
[ESPINOSA]: are connected to health, are connected to everything we do.

215
00:20:54,596 --> 00:21:01,958
[ESPINOSA]: So any response to the climate emergency has to factor in this complexity.

216
00:21:02,058 --> 00:21:07,320
[ESPINOSA]: But how can you factor in the complexity is to bring all the actors together.

217
00:21:07,760 --> 00:21:09,580
[ESPINOSA]: You said something very important, Liz.

218
00:21:10,381 --> 00:21:18,843
[ESPINOSA]: If you ask a person coming from Mars or Jupiter that we have met 31 times soon now in Turkey,

219
00:21:19,613 --> 00:21:28,319
[ESPINOSA]: on conference of the parties to discuss and negotiate climate agreements and after 31 years emissions continue to grow.

220
00:21:28,919 --> 00:21:36,644
[ESPINOSA]: There is a huge implementation gap that we have to deal with and one of the answers to that is

221
00:21:37,188 --> 00:21:47,899
[ESPINOSA]: the complexity address climate change from a peace and security perspective, from a conflict perspective, from a health perspective, from a development perspective.

222
00:21:48,380 --> 00:21:52,864
[ESPINOSA]: It is the defining challenge of our times.

223
00:21:53,405 --> 00:21:55,787
[ESPINOSA]: Complexity requires complex responses.

224
00:21:56,528 --> 00:21:58,350
[ESPINOSA]: well organized responses.

225
00:21:58,510 --> 00:22:08,338
[ESPINOSA]: I have to say within the UN, I would say there is a need for greater coherence, less duplication and better working together within the system.

226
00:22:08,518 --> 00:22:13,062
[ESPINOSA]: I have seen it from the outside and I think it needs a major restructuring.

227
00:22:14,462 --> 00:22:21,585
[ESPINOSA]: the UN delivering as one on climate, supporting member states to respond to the climate challenges of today.

228
00:22:22,745 --> 00:22:28,107
[ESPINOSA]: And just to say one more sentence, I am here representing a small island developing state.

229
00:22:28,815 --> 00:22:32,836
[ESPINOSA]: I know, I know closely what a climate shock can do.

230
00:22:33,156 --> 00:22:39,257
[ESPINOSA]: It can devastate and erase the entire infrastructure of a country.

231
00:22:39,578 --> 00:22:42,178
[ESPINOSA]: So it is the defining challenge of our time.

232
00:22:42,618 --> 00:22:43,658
[SPEAKER_04]: We're running out of time.

233
00:22:43,779 --> 00:22:45,139
[SPEAKER_04]: I have one last question.

234
00:22:45,879 --> 00:22:49,640
[SPEAKER_04]: And it is from Ian Bell from Northeast Hertfordshire of the Labour Party.

235
00:22:50,520 --> 00:22:52,743
[SPEAKER_04]: in the United Kingdom, the governing Labour Party.

236
00:22:53,283 --> 00:23:08,800
[SPEAKER_04]: His question, can we, given we are on course to fall short of the UN sustainability goals by 2030, do you think they have to be rethought to fit into today's ever increasing world of isolationism, tariffs and aid cuts?

237
00:23:09,220 --> 00:23:11,062
[SPEAKER_04]: And if they are going to be rethought, how?

238
00:23:13,168 --> 00:23:17,813
[ESPINOSA]: I think the Sustainable Development Goals are the right ambition.

239
00:23:18,014 --> 00:23:18,754
[ESPINOSA]: I said that.

240
00:23:23,267 --> 00:23:25,788
[ESPINOSA]: a reference and aspirational agenda.

241
00:23:25,948 --> 00:23:27,329
[ESPINOSA]: And I think it's very important.

242
00:23:27,749 --> 00:23:30,991
[ESPINOSA]: It's one of the big successes of multilateralism.

243
00:23:31,791 --> 00:23:44,558
[ESPINOSA]: And what I would do before we get to 2030 is put in motion the acceleration plans for implementation, of course, but I think that the UN cannot be

244
00:23:45,815 --> 00:23:49,298
[ESPINOSA]: an implementer of development projects on the ground.

245
00:23:49,458 --> 00:23:58,566
[ESPINOSA]: I said development has to be owned by countries because developing countries, and I come from one, we need three things.

246
00:23:59,286 --> 00:24:00,568
[ESPINOSA]: And that's what I would work on.

247
00:24:01,148 --> 00:24:06,935
[ESPINOSA]: The money, mobilized resources, the technologies, and the capacity, strong institutions.

248
00:24:07,015 --> 00:24:10,359
[ESPINOSA]: But the development cannot be delivered from New York.

249
00:24:10,459 --> 00:24:16,246
[ESPINOSA]: It has to be delivered under the rule of local first, the subsidiarity principle.

250
00:24:17,768 --> 00:24:30,298
[SPEAKER_04]: Last question but it's very short answer because we are over time but in interest of fairness, it's one of the toughest jobs in the world but the citizens don't want you falling asleep at your desk or going mad.

251
00:24:30,758 --> 00:24:32,520
[SPEAKER_04]: Very briefly, how will you relax?

252
00:24:35,300 --> 00:24:45,128
[ESPINOSA]: Well, I will go to the first botanical garden next to me, if it's all buildings, because I think that nature gives you the energy.

253
00:24:45,568 --> 00:24:50,032
[ESPINOSA]: But I will also listen to elders and the elders that I grew up with.

254
00:24:50,632 --> 00:24:55,155
[ESPINOSA]: especially the ones I spent five years with in the Ecuadorian Amazon.

255
00:24:55,475 --> 00:25:00,839
[ESPINOSA]: That was my school, my university, where I learned solidarity and resilience the most.

256
00:25:01,139 --> 00:25:02,320
[ESPINOSA]: I will call one of them.

257
00:25:02,540 --> 00:25:04,501
[ESPINOSA]: They do have cell phones these days.

258
00:25:04,801 --> 00:25:07,003
[ESPINOSA]: At the time where I was living at the Amazon, they didn't.

259
00:25:07,383 --> 00:25:11,866
[ESPINOSA]: So I will listen to the voices of wisdom and connect to nature.

260
00:25:12,186 --> 00:25:13,127
[ESPINOSA]: To some tree baby.

261
00:25:13,507 --> 00:25:15,649
[SPEAKER_04]: Maria Fernanda Espinosa, thank you very much.

262
00:25:15,669 --> 00:25:16,069
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you, Liz.

263
00:25:16,229 --> 00:25:16,709
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

264
00:25:16,990 --> 00:25:17,390
[ESPINOSA]: Thank you.

265
00:25:20,738 --> 00:25:21,119
[ESPINOSA]: Thank you.

266
00:25:21,621 --> 00:25:22,343
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you so much.

267
00:25:22,363 --> 00:25:22,824
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

268
00:25:23,085 --> 00:25:23,486
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

269
00:25:23,526 --> 00:25:23,947
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

